WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.360
So yeah, I'd like to thank everyone for attending this Ask Hadley Anything, which will be for

00:00:09.360 --> 00:00:10.960
the next half hour.

00:00:10.960 --> 00:00:17.920
Usar is coming up with just under a month to go in Salzburg this year, and Hadley is

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:23.440
a presenter, so there's a chance at that event to hear more from him, but today he's here

00:00:23.440 --> 00:00:27.719
as representing one of our sponsors that made Usar possible.

00:00:28.440 --> 00:00:29.080
So yeah, thank you.

00:00:29.080 --> 00:00:33.639
I guess, Hadley, could you give us a little quicker intro to yourself and our sponsor,

00:00:33.639 --> 00:00:34.139
Puzzlet?

00:00:35.560 --> 00:00:36.279
Yeah, sure.

00:00:36.279 --> 00:00:36.919
Thanks, Jane.

00:00:36.919 --> 00:00:37.720
Thanks for having me.

00:00:38.680 --> 00:00:47.320
So as you probably know, I write a lot of R packages, and me and my team look after the

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:53.080
tidyverse, which is a set of packages for doing data science, and kind of the DevTools

00:00:53.080 --> 00:00:57.720
ecosystem of packages, which help folks maintain their own packages.

00:00:57.720 --> 00:01:02.119
So for example, one of the things I've been working on recently is Packagedown, which

00:01:02.119 --> 00:01:08.440
is the R package that we use to make websites for our other R packages, and now many other

00:01:08.440 --> 00:01:11.639
people use that package for their package websites too.

00:01:13.320 --> 00:01:19.239
So Puzzlet, I work for Puzzlet, which is a PBC, or a Public Benefit Corp.

00:01:19.239 --> 00:01:21.959
That's a little bit different to the traditional LLC.

00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:30.120
In an LLC, the kind of overarching goal of every LLC is to maximize shareholder revenue.

00:01:31.239 --> 00:01:34.760
That's kind of the mission of every LLC.

00:01:34.760 --> 00:01:40.440
The idea of a PBC is to relax that and to add some goals other than just making a ton

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:41.320
of money.

00:01:41.320 --> 00:01:48.120
And so the goals of Puzzlet are to really support the data science ecosystems, R and

00:01:48.120 --> 00:01:51.160
Python, and scientific publishing in general.

00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:56.599
So we make a lot of open source software, but we also sell commercial products.

00:01:57.720 --> 00:02:03.879
Our main commercial products are Puzzlet Workbench, Puzzlet Connect, and Puzzlet Package

00:02:03.879 --> 00:02:11.880
Manager, basically designed to solve problems that larger teams of R users tend to have.

00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:18.919
So Puzzlet Workbench allows you to run RStudio or VS Code or Jupyter Notebooks on centralized

00:02:18.919 --> 00:02:24.119
compute, which allows you to have a few big servers with a lot of computing power, or

00:02:24.119 --> 00:02:28.679
perhaps you're in a regulated environment, and that allows you to run all your code in

00:02:28.679 --> 00:02:30.839
an environment where everything's set up correctly.

00:02:32.520 --> 00:02:38.679
Connect allows you to get the results of your analysis basically out of your hand and the

00:02:38.679 --> 00:02:47.000
decision makers, whether that's by publishing Shiny apps or Dash apps or scheduled R markdowns

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:52.119
or sending an email with a link to a dashboard at 9 a.m. on every Friday.

00:02:53.639 --> 00:02:59.240
And then last but not least is Puzzlet Package Manager, which basically allows your organization

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:05.720
to use a shared set of packages that have all the qualities that your organization might

00:03:05.720 --> 00:03:06.220
want.

00:03:06.940 --> 00:03:14.139
So that was a very quick overview, but I work on the open source side of Puzzlet, but tremendously

00:03:14.139 --> 00:03:17.899
grateful for all of my colleagues who do make products.

00:03:17.899 --> 00:03:20.539
They waste a lot of money because they pay for my salary.

00:03:22.139 --> 00:03:23.259
Awesome, thank you.

00:03:23.259 --> 00:03:27.899
And I guess also thanks to everyone because the questions are already coming in, but maybe

00:03:27.899 --> 00:03:34.220
starting broad with one of our earlier questions, what, and you're not allowed to use the Puzzlet

00:03:34.220 --> 00:03:36.300
example here, like open source project.

00:03:36.300 --> 00:03:38.380
Have you gotten excited about recently?

00:03:42.380 --> 00:03:48.059
I'll tell you, I've been playing around a little bit with VS Code, which is a pretty

00:03:48.059 --> 00:03:52.380
interesting IDE or almost not exactly an IDE.

00:03:52.380 --> 00:03:57.339
It's almost like a tool for building your own IDE, but just been playing around with

00:03:57.339 --> 00:04:00.619
that, learning a bit about how it works.

00:04:00.619 --> 00:04:02.059
And that's been pretty interesting.

00:04:02.139 --> 00:04:09.339
Just a very, very popular IDE used by all sorts of developers for other languages, which

00:04:09.339 --> 00:04:14.539
has been interesting to see what folks expect in kind of a modern IDE.

00:04:15.820 --> 00:04:20.619
Okay, and I think that leads quite well into both a question we had before and a question

00:04:20.619 --> 00:04:25.899
that's just popped into the chat, but there was one there around like, what is your preferred

00:04:25.899 --> 00:04:29.660
IDE and does it change depending on what you're doing?

00:04:29.660 --> 00:04:34.299
So examples being R package development, Python development, general data science,

00:04:34.299 --> 00:04:38.299
the one just in the chat is Shiny, as well as things like Koto websites.

00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:44.140
Yeah, I will say like 90% of what I do is package development.

00:04:45.100 --> 00:04:49.260
I do like a little bit of other things, hardly any package development, but a little bit

00:04:49.260 --> 00:04:54.059
of Shiny development, a few websites, a little bit of data science from time to time.

00:04:54.059 --> 00:04:59.980
So I really like to kind of like stick with as much as possible with one thing so I can

00:04:59.980 --> 00:05:02.859
really get familiar with it.

00:05:02.859 --> 00:05:08.299
So currently that means it's sort of a mix of RStudio, which is my kind of day-to-day

00:05:08.299 --> 00:05:12.940
driver and then BS Code, which I'm just exploring and learning from.

00:05:15.100 --> 00:05:15.579
Thank you.

00:05:16.540 --> 00:05:22.299
And you touched on this a little bit in your intro, but one of the questions was like today,

00:05:22.299 --> 00:05:24.299
what are the projects that you're working on?

00:05:25.579 --> 00:05:34.299
Yeah, so package, I'm currently getting very close to finishing off a package down release.

00:05:35.179 --> 00:05:39.980
I think that kind of the two big features in this release are going to be having like

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:41.899
optional dark mode for your website.

00:05:41.899 --> 00:05:45.980
So the users of your package website can flip between light mode and dark mode.

00:05:47.019 --> 00:05:50.540
It's very, very popular feature on websites.

00:05:51.100 --> 00:05:57.260
And that's a little bit more significantly as the ability to use Quarto for your

00:05:58.299 --> 00:05:59.820
vignettes and your packages.

00:05:59.820 --> 00:06:04.059
So traditionally, people have written their vignettes using R Markdown.

00:06:04.059 --> 00:06:07.739
Fairly recently, CRAN has installed Quarto.

00:06:07.739 --> 00:06:13.420
And so now you can use Quarto to write your vignettes, which brings up like all of the

00:06:13.420 --> 00:06:22.700
nice features that Quarto have from better figure layout and easier cross-referencing

00:06:22.700 --> 00:06:24.779
and equations and all that kind of stuff.

00:06:24.779 --> 00:06:27.500
So bringing that to your package vignettes as well.

00:06:28.540 --> 00:06:36.540
And that's kind of a dark art because you've got to merge the templating systems of package

00:06:36.540 --> 00:06:37.899
down and Quarto together.

00:06:38.459 --> 00:06:44.859
So it's certainly never going to be like 100% perfect, but I think we can get to like 95%

00:06:44.859 --> 00:06:48.459
pretty easily and get most of the features that people care about working.

00:06:48.459 --> 00:06:52.940
And then as people report them, we'll fix bugs and stuff.

00:06:52.940 --> 00:06:56.380
But that should be coming very, very, very soon.

00:06:58.059 --> 00:06:58.459
Thank you.

00:06:59.579 --> 00:07:02.540
And there was a question come in, which I think maybe touches a little bit on, I can't

00:07:02.540 --> 00:07:07.260
remember if it was your workshop or your talk, but someone said that they recently saw a

00:07:07.260 --> 00:07:12.140
video where you showed an example of web scraping and GitHub automation.

00:07:12.779 --> 00:07:18.540
And they asked, is there a possible use to use GitHub to automatically render multiple

00:07:18.540 --> 00:07:22.859
Quarto documents to PDF and HTML and upload them to a server?

00:07:24.220 --> 00:07:25.339
Yeah, absolutely.

00:07:27.660 --> 00:07:33.260
I can just show you, let's see, I think I managed to get this working like five seconds

00:07:33.260 --> 00:07:34.299
before, that's cool.

00:07:34.859 --> 00:07:39.019
So let me see if I can get that page.

00:07:51.420 --> 00:07:56.220
Well, let's put the link in the chat anyway.

00:07:57.739 --> 00:08:02.220
Hopefully it will be working later, but I was just playing around with this today.

00:08:02.940 --> 00:08:11.820
Now, Crayon just released, they're now making it more clear which packages are possibly

00:08:11.820 --> 00:08:14.380
scheduled for removal if they haven't fixed problems.

00:08:15.179 --> 00:08:19.820
So I've been working just to turn that into like a little dashboard that gets automatically

00:08:19.820 --> 00:08:22.459
updated every day by GitHub Action.

00:08:23.019 --> 00:08:36.380
So I seem to have missed some steps, so the action is working, but I can't see where it

00:08:36.380 --> 00:08:39.659
is publishing.

00:08:44.460 --> 00:08:48.940
But anyway, I think this sort of...

00:08:48.940 --> 00:08:51.900
Why is that not working?

00:08:55.900 --> 00:08:58.059
We're making you do something, a live demo.

00:08:58.059 --> 00:09:03.900
But this sort of thing, I think where you schedule a GitHub Action or something similar

00:09:03.900 --> 00:09:09.260
to do something and then publish it somewhere is like super, super useful, super powerful.

00:09:10.380 --> 00:09:15.500
And like basically you can do it today, it's just not terribly well documented.

00:09:15.500 --> 00:09:21.020
So one of the things I've been sort of thinking more generally about lately is this issue

00:09:21.020 --> 00:09:23.979
of like, how do you effectively use R in production?

00:09:24.780 --> 00:09:31.340
And to me, production, like the two, I think, big things that make putting R or putting

00:09:31.340 --> 00:09:36.140
anything in production challenging is that you've got to run your code is now being run

00:09:36.140 --> 00:09:39.580
like regularly and it's being run on another computer.

00:09:39.580 --> 00:09:44.380
So I'm trying to do more and more of these things in GitHub Actions, these regular things

00:09:44.380 --> 00:09:49.739
just to better learn, like how can you write code that is both more reliable and when it

00:09:49.739 --> 00:09:51.900
fails, gives you more actionable insights.

00:09:51.900 --> 00:09:57.580
So hopefully I'll get this particular one working.

00:09:57.580 --> 00:10:01.820
And then as I set up a few more of them, I have to kind of start to document that process

00:10:01.820 --> 00:10:04.219
a bit better so other people can copy it.

00:10:05.179 --> 00:10:13.500
Another thing I did sort of along a similar lines, probably the video you saw was there

00:10:13.500 --> 00:10:18.619
was an artist I follow on TikTok and every time he sold his work, it was always sold

00:10:18.619 --> 00:10:20.299
out by the time I found out about it.

00:10:20.299 --> 00:10:26.380
So I wrote a little script to Scraper's website every three hours and then send a push notification

00:10:26.380 --> 00:10:33.260
to my phone whenever it changed so that I could finally buy some of the art.

00:10:33.260 --> 00:10:37.340
So I think there's a lot of cool little things you can do with GitHub Actions in that way.

00:10:37.340 --> 00:10:40.299
And I want to try and make this accessible to more people.

00:10:41.260 --> 00:10:41.260


00:10:43.260 --> 00:10:48.059
And then maybe changing tack a little bit, I'm attacking a little bit, but there's one

00:10:48.059 --> 00:10:54.059
question here around how does PositBalance having packages that they continue to support,

00:10:54.059 --> 00:11:00.059
like all the ones in the tidyverse, without the effort to keep these packages supported,

00:11:00.059 --> 00:11:01.979
not leaving capacity to do anything new?

00:11:03.739 --> 00:11:07.659
Yeah, I mean, that's a really tough challenge.

00:11:07.739 --> 00:11:15.979
And I think the other aspect of this that we're starting to learn about is that most

00:11:15.979 --> 00:11:21.260
people tend to get sick of maintaining the same package after somewhere between five

00:11:21.260 --> 00:11:22.460
and 10 years.

00:11:23.659 --> 00:11:24.619
So that's kind of happened.

00:11:24.619 --> 00:11:29.419
Let's sort of have what's happened with me and ggplot2, I love it, it's still close to

00:11:29.419 --> 00:11:32.460
my heart, but after so many years, you just want to do something else.

00:11:33.260 --> 00:11:39.179
And so the original strategy was to hire, well, the original fix was to hire Thomas

00:11:39.179 --> 00:11:40.700
Peterson to maintain it.

00:11:40.700 --> 00:11:43.900
And now he's getting sick of maintaining it.

00:11:43.900 --> 00:11:50.219
And so obviously hiring a new person every time is not a terribly scalable strategy.

00:11:50.940 --> 00:11:53.820
So I think, I don't know, I don't have any great insights here.

00:11:53.820 --> 00:11:57.820
I think one of the things we're trying to be more clear about in the tidyverse is just

00:11:57.820 --> 00:12:02.940
our development cadence and how many packages most of the time are just kind of lying in

00:12:02.940 --> 00:12:04.299
this fallow state.

00:12:04.299 --> 00:12:09.099
We will keep them on CRAN, we will fix any kind of critical bugs that we come across,

00:12:09.739 --> 00:12:13.979
but they're mostly just kind of lying there, accumulating issues until we notice, oh,

00:12:13.979 --> 00:12:18.700
hey, there's a couple of weeks worth on this package, and then we'll come back to it.

00:12:19.979 --> 00:12:25.099
But I think in general, the thing that is tough is saying no to people.

00:12:25.099 --> 00:12:31.020
And I think we have gotten better at that a bit in terms of just being like, hey, this

00:12:31.020 --> 00:12:31.979
is a cool idea.

00:12:33.659 --> 00:12:37.419
We'd love to do it, but we just don't have the time and we're probably never going to

00:12:37.419 --> 00:12:37.979
have the time.

00:12:37.979 --> 00:12:42.299
And so closing issues down for that reason, which kind of sucks.

00:12:42.299 --> 00:12:49.419
But we have to carve out the time and the energy to work on new stuff as well as maintaining

00:12:49.419 --> 00:12:49.979
old stuff.

00:12:49.979 --> 00:12:53.260
So that's the bummer.

00:12:54.219 --> 00:12:54.719
OK.

00:12:55.820 --> 00:12:59.739
And there's one question here specifically about BSlib.

00:12:59.739 --> 00:13:04.380
And so the person's mentioning that it's becoming a one-stop shop for Shiny dashboard

00:13:04.380 --> 00:13:05.020
development.

00:13:05.659 --> 00:13:09.260
But what additional functionality would you like to see added to the package?

00:13:10.940 --> 00:13:11.739
Yeah, I don't have...

00:13:13.099 --> 00:13:20.619
I use BSlib mostly in kind of weird or unusual ways because I'm using it for like package

00:13:20.700 --> 00:13:23.900
down or for other bits and pieces.

00:13:23.900 --> 00:13:31.419
I think most recently been exploring the idea of adding like a gallery page to package down

00:13:31.419 --> 00:13:34.859
sites that use BSlib cards.

00:13:36.219 --> 00:13:39.340
And that, I don't know, that always seems to work pretty well.

00:13:40.380 --> 00:13:41.340
It's definitely a little...

00:13:41.340 --> 00:13:47.099
I think that's the challenge I have with BSlib is it's often hard to figure out.

00:13:47.099 --> 00:13:52.539
Like you've got to kind of cross-reference the BSlib docs or the Bootstrap docs to figure

00:13:52.539 --> 00:13:55.979
out if there's something specific that you're trying to achieve.

00:13:55.979 --> 00:13:59.580
Sometimes it's just easier to write the HTML yourself.

00:13:59.580 --> 00:14:01.419
So I don't know.

00:14:01.419 --> 00:14:02.140
I don't have any...

00:14:02.140 --> 00:14:03.179
Yeah, I don't have anything.

00:14:03.179 --> 00:14:07.900
I don't feel particularly limited by BSlib just because you can always go out and write

00:14:07.900 --> 00:14:09.419
the HTML yourself if you want.

00:14:11.820 --> 00:14:16.700
And there were a few questions kind of asking for updates on specific topics.

00:14:16.859 --> 00:14:24.140
So maybe looking across ggviz, Mastering Shiny, and also dbply.

00:14:24.140 --> 00:14:29.419
I guess, is there anything hot off the news or coming for those three projects?

00:14:29.419 --> 00:14:34.380
Yeah, ggviz is definitely unlikely that we'll see another upgrade.

00:14:35.580 --> 00:14:42.219
But Thomas is starting to think about kind of what the future of graphics should look like.

00:14:42.780 --> 00:14:47.739
And it's not kind of super clear exactly what that should be and how that ties in

00:14:47.739 --> 00:14:49.659
with web graphics and reactivity.

00:14:50.539 --> 00:14:53.580
But he's starting to do a bunch of projects to kind of explore that.

00:14:53.580 --> 00:14:59.340
So nothing in the near future, but definitely something that he's going to think more about.

00:15:02.140 --> 00:15:07.260
Mastering Shiny, I don't have any current plans to update it.

00:15:08.219 --> 00:15:13.260
But we've talked about doing like a translation of Mastering Shiny to Python.

00:15:14.780 --> 00:15:20.539
I think that's probably more likely to happen first, just as we try and help Python folks

00:15:20.539 --> 00:15:21.820
master Shiny as well.

00:15:23.500 --> 00:15:26.460
And then dbply, I don't know, it's just like a steady...

00:15:27.580 --> 00:15:32.140
I think dbply seems to be like a pretty important package for a lot of people.

00:15:32.140 --> 00:15:37.260
And we'll just continue to see like a steady stream of fixes and improvements.

00:15:38.140 --> 00:15:46.059
I'm really grateful that dbply now has another maintainer, Maximillian

00:15:48.059 --> 00:15:51.820
who has been contributing a lot of the fixes lately.

00:15:51.820 --> 00:16:00.140
So it's been really great to have someone else thinking about it and caring about it.

00:16:00.140 --> 00:16:04.780
So there's definitely a package, it's just a long tail of small issues and just like

00:16:04.780 --> 00:16:08.380
grinding down all these minor SQL translation problems.

00:16:09.820 --> 00:16:12.940
I think the only thing that I'll be kind of like specifically

00:16:15.179 --> 00:16:19.659
kind of pitching in on that in the database ecosystem at the moment is just around integration

00:16:19.659 --> 00:16:20.539
with our partners.

00:16:21.179 --> 00:16:25.500
Both of us now partnering with Databricks and Snowflake and just doing anything I can

00:16:25.500 --> 00:16:29.340
do on the open source side to make sure if you are using Databricks or Snowflake that

00:16:29.340 --> 00:16:35.419
everything just like works seamlessly and painlessly from our studio and from our packages.

00:16:35.419 --> 00:16:39.659
You don't have to like fretting about all the various different things,

00:16:40.299 --> 00:16:43.340
just works and like disappears into the background.

00:16:45.739 --> 00:16:46.219
Okay.

00:16:46.219 --> 00:16:51.020
And as you mentioned the potential translation for the Python community,

00:16:51.020 --> 00:16:52.780
there's a couple of questions in that space.

00:16:52.780 --> 00:16:55.739
I think one I liked the wording, the way it was worded was

00:16:56.619 --> 00:17:01.260
what type of topics you discuss when you have a work meeting with Wes McKinney?

00:17:02.859 --> 00:17:08.459
Yeah, I think a lot of what we discussed is how to make R and Python work better together.

00:17:09.260 --> 00:17:14.540
And I think that's kind of a story there is the same as it's been for quite a long time.

00:17:14.540 --> 00:17:19.339
It's just like a lot of stuff that you don't want to write in R or Python,

00:17:19.339 --> 00:17:24.300
you want to write in like C or C++ or Rust or some other high performance programming language.

00:17:24.859 --> 00:17:30.459
And then on top of that, you build a nice user interface in R or Python.

00:17:31.339 --> 00:17:33.660
I think like we've seen that with like DuckDB,

00:17:34.939 --> 00:17:38.060
we've seen that with like some interesting work in Polars.

00:17:39.420 --> 00:17:45.579
It's just, I don't know, like a reticulate package in R makes that easier to talk between the two.

00:17:45.579 --> 00:17:52.300
The Arrow project, the sharing data across them, that just feels, I don't know, like in some way,

00:17:52.300 --> 00:17:56.060
it feels to me like it's just getting easier and easier to collaborate across these boundaries.

00:17:57.579 --> 00:18:03.579
One thing that Gabor Ciardi and my team did recently was write a little package for reading

00:18:03.579 --> 00:18:09.979
parquet files into R. You can certainly do that with Arrow, but Arrow is like a big heavy

00:18:09.979 --> 00:18:16.619
dependency. This is like, I think we call it a nano parquet. It is a very, very lightweight

00:18:16.619 --> 00:18:23.660
package, but it just makes it easier to use this pretty standard file format in R if you're

00:18:23.660 --> 00:18:29.180
working with smaller datasets as well. So it's kind of continuing to look for opportunities to

00:18:29.180 --> 00:18:35.420
collaborate across language boundaries. Okay. And there was another question which was worded,

00:18:35.979 --> 00:18:41.180
how do you see the role of R and its ecosystem evolving to meet the growing number of data

00:18:41.180 --> 00:18:46.380
scientists that also know generic Python languages like Python? And I guess maybe you've

00:18:46.380 --> 00:18:52.140
talked a little bit about the interoperability, but do you think R and R scope and with the focus

00:18:52.140 --> 00:18:58.140
of R and its ecosystem would be impacted by the introduction of more Python or?

00:18:59.180 --> 00:19:08.540
Yeah. I mean, it's interesting because Python is legitimately the most popular programming

00:19:08.540 --> 00:19:13.900
language on the planet right now, incredibly powerful general purpose tool. And there's

00:19:13.900 --> 00:19:19.339
obviously a lot of advantages to having one tool that you turn to for every problem you

00:19:19.339 --> 00:19:25.180
could possibly imagine. And that's Python. But there's also advantages to working with tools

00:19:25.180 --> 00:19:31.660
that specialize for the problem at hand. Because Python, there's just no way that in Python,

00:19:31.660 --> 00:19:36.780
you're ever going to be able to, I think, interact with data as fluidly as you can with R because of

00:19:36.780 --> 00:19:42.140
the way that missing values are built into the language because of the way non-standard evaluation

00:19:42.140 --> 00:19:50.140
works and R allows us to write interfaces like ggplot2 and dplyr. Yeah, sure, the R community

00:19:50.140 --> 00:19:56.380
is smaller and there's lots of things that R can't do that Python can do. But I don't know.

00:19:56.380 --> 00:20:02.859
I think at the end of the day, we can have general purpose tools and we can have special purpose

00:20:02.859 --> 00:20:09.099
tools. And I love R and I have no intention of stopping developing.

00:20:12.459 --> 00:20:19.099
And then there's one here. We talked a little bit about working with constraints on resources.

00:20:19.099 --> 00:20:24.619
There's a question here about in a hypothetical scenario where you had unlimited resources,

00:20:25.260 --> 00:20:28.459
is there a project that you would even want to start or revive?

00:20:28.459 --> 00:20:39.739
I think one of the projects that's really interesting to me is these tools for

00:20:40.939 --> 00:20:50.060
gradual typing where you add types to a programming language. TypeScript's a good example of this or

00:20:50.859 --> 00:20:58.780
Pydandic's kind of in this space too, where the advantage of adding types being very

00:20:58.780 --> 00:21:03.579
strict for every function about what sorts of inputs it can take and what sort of outputs it

00:21:03.579 --> 00:21:09.979
produces, it leads to better documentation, leads to better error messages, and potentially

00:21:09.979 --> 00:21:18.859
leads to much better performance. But languages with strict type systems are pretty far away from

00:21:18.859 --> 00:21:23.420
R. But I think there's been interesting research lately and how you can kind of gradually add

00:21:23.420 --> 00:21:30.060
types into more dynamic languages. That would be a big project. It's kind of hard to tell

00:21:30.780 --> 00:21:34.619
what the payouts would be in the long run, but I think that would be something I would love to

00:21:35.180 --> 00:21:43.819
invest more on and just figure out how we can make our programs both safer and faster and

00:21:44.619 --> 00:21:56.140
more informative when they error. Thank you. I guess it wouldn't be a Q&A in 2024 without a LLM

00:21:56.140 --> 00:22:01.579
question. There's one here on, what's your opinion on the future of data science

00:22:03.180 --> 00:22:08.540
during the era of tools like, they mentioned ChatGBT, but I guess there's also GitHub Copilot

00:22:08.540 --> 00:22:20.219
and similar IDE-based tools. Yeah, I find it very hard to imagine that you can replace a

00:22:20.219 --> 00:22:27.020
data scientist with anything less than kind of full-on generalized AI, because you have to bring

00:22:27.020 --> 00:22:32.619
so much domain knowledge and expertise to any problem apart from just writing code.

00:22:33.420 --> 00:22:39.099
But I do think that LLMs are going to have a pretty transformative impact on the way that we

00:22:39.979 --> 00:22:46.859
write code. And certainly, I think it seems like it fundamentally changes how we might teach

00:22:46.859 --> 00:22:53.260
programming, because now you can express yourself in English or whatever, express yourself in a

00:22:53.260 --> 00:23:02.380
human language and get pretty reasonable code a lot of the time generated. I use Copilot. I've

00:23:02.380 --> 00:23:14.699
found it really interesting and useful, particularly at doing tedious tasks or changing

00:23:14.699 --> 00:23:19.339
things between two different structures. It seems to be pretty good at figuring out,

00:23:20.060 --> 00:23:26.300
guessing the old structure and the new structure, and then prompting me. So there's things that

00:23:26.380 --> 00:23:33.900
kind of routine bits of programming that I found it really helpful for. I think in general,

00:23:35.660 --> 00:23:39.260
it's really good at that kind of lower level, like pretty good at that lower level. Sometimes

00:23:39.260 --> 00:23:45.579
it just does a lot of things. But it doesn't, I don't know, I don't think it provides much sense

00:23:45.579 --> 00:23:52.300
of direction. So there still really needs to be that human in the loop, steering the direction

00:23:52.300 --> 00:23:57.180
and thinking about the bigger picture and what's the overall goal. And I think we're a very long

00:23:57.180 --> 00:24:05.819
way away from having LLMs to solve that gap. I think LLMs are really, really good at solving

00:24:05.819 --> 00:24:10.300
problems that have been solved a ton of times before, because it can just average out over all

00:24:10.300 --> 00:24:15.099
of those problems that are seen on the internet, the things that have never been done before. It's

00:24:15.180 --> 00:24:23.900
just clearly not as good. And I guess I'm very skeptical that we can kind of bootstrap genuine

00:24:26.140 --> 00:24:30.859
inferential capabilities just by throwing more and more data at it.

00:24:33.739 --> 00:24:35.819
Maybe setting this on one of my own questions. So like,

00:24:37.579 --> 00:24:41.819
for people like yourself and those at Posit that are professional package maintainers and

00:24:41.819 --> 00:24:46.699
developers, do you find the code completions, I guess, if you have code completions enabled,

00:24:47.260 --> 00:24:52.939
does any of that get, you know, you tab it in? Or is it something where it's not using the correct

00:24:52.939 --> 00:24:57.339
style or it's not referencing? I'm just interested if it's the code completions.

00:24:57.339 --> 00:25:04.219
I'm tabbing it in quite a lot. But again, I've noticed it's really good. If I'm going to write

00:25:04.219 --> 00:25:10.939
for a function, I've written the documentation and now I want to check that each argument is the

00:25:10.939 --> 00:25:16.939
correct type. And once I've done the first two arguments, it's pretty good at just stepping

00:25:16.939 --> 00:25:21.420
through all the other arguments and guessing what function I want to call to check its type.

00:25:21.420 --> 00:25:25.180
So it's stuff like that where it's like, I would have figured that out. It wouldn't have taken me

00:25:25.180 --> 00:25:29.660
that long to type it. But now I can just press tab and complete the whole thing instead of having to

00:25:30.300 --> 00:25:37.819
think about it. Sometimes that's a good thing. And sometimes it's a bad thing because you just,

00:25:38.780 --> 00:25:43.900
it's easy. It's also easy for subtle mistakes to creep in that way because you didn't really

00:25:43.900 --> 00:25:49.020
think about it. You didn't really read it. So there's definitely also a cost of just

00:25:49.900 --> 00:25:55.260
tabbing in larger blocks of code because sometimes the effort of understanding exactly what you just

00:25:55.260 --> 00:26:00.699
did is greater than the cost of writing it yourself. But I'm definitely noticing I'm

00:26:00.699 --> 00:26:05.819
kind of relying on it more. And even if it gets half the suggestion right, it's still

00:26:05.819 --> 00:26:08.459
useful to tab that out and then delete and change the rest of it.

00:26:10.219 --> 00:26:16.060
Okay. And so we have some questions that we won't be able to get to here. So I'll try to follow up,

00:26:16.060 --> 00:26:20.780
especially the ones that are asking questions about Posit products. So we can maybe get some

00:26:20.780 --> 00:26:26.219
help from the Posit team there. There's one here though, I guess from someone quite passionate to

00:26:26.219 --> 00:26:32.380
know, if they want to become, so they're asking about becoming a data scientist at Posit. So I

00:26:32.380 --> 00:26:37.260
guess my first question is, does that exist? And then just generally, if you did want to become an

00:26:37.260 --> 00:26:42.619
engineer at Posit, what makes a Positier or whatever Posit calls themselves?

00:26:45.500 --> 00:26:51.339
Yeah. So we do have a data science team. It's pretty small. I think it's about four people

00:26:51.339 --> 00:26:57.979
currently and it's pretty small and it's pretty scrappy. And I will say my experience as a data

00:26:57.979 --> 00:27:03.579
science team at Posit has exactly the same problems that small data science teams have

00:27:03.579 --> 00:27:09.819
at every single company where they exist. It's challenging to get high quality data.

00:27:10.540 --> 00:27:16.300
It's challenging to create dashboards that yield actionable insights that don't have

00:27:17.099 --> 00:27:23.260
various execs trying to change things all the time. So I think because we have a small data

00:27:23.260 --> 00:27:31.020
science team, if you want to be a data scientist at Posit, you have to be strong and

00:27:31.020 --> 00:27:35.739
you've got to be able to act pretty independently and know a little bit about

00:27:35.739 --> 00:27:39.660
all the parts of the data science pipeline. You're likely to be doing a little bit of data

00:27:39.660 --> 00:27:44.140
engineering. You're going to be writing some R code. You're going to be writing shiny apps. You'll

00:27:44.140 --> 00:27:52.140
be writing dashboards. You've got to have the full stack of experience there.

00:27:53.900 --> 00:27:58.219
And engineering more broadly, like on the open source side, we're looking for people

00:27:58.219 --> 00:28:05.099
that are generally contributed to the R ecosystem already, present on GitHub. And it's certainly

00:28:05.099 --> 00:28:11.260
very easy. It's much easier to hire people that we have interacted with positively in the past

00:28:11.260 --> 00:28:16.619
because we know you're going to be a good fit with the team already. But we also have a bunch

00:28:16.619 --> 00:28:23.420
of just general engineers who are, I think if you read the R community, like Posit is a company

00:28:23.420 --> 00:28:31.339
that you know and hopefully respect. And the broader developer ecosystem, Posit is just like

00:28:31.339 --> 00:28:37.099
a tiny company amongst thousands of other companies. And it's a totally different ballgame

00:28:37.099 --> 00:28:42.380
hiring just general engineers because most of them don't know about Posit at all or what we're

00:28:42.380 --> 00:28:48.060
trying to do. And there I think it's just about the kind of general programming skills and having

00:28:48.060 --> 00:28:54.459
some interest in data science. And maybe just to close us out, there's a question from Sierra here

00:28:54.459 --> 00:29:01.660
about if you know R and you want to take the step of getting involved in an open source project,

00:29:01.660 --> 00:29:07.420
I guess do you have any tips there for someone who's never contributed to someone else's code

00:29:07.420 --> 00:29:13.180
in an open source setting before? Yeah, I think my advice is to like start small and get

00:29:14.380 --> 00:29:19.339
accustomed to kind of the technical process of like how do you make a pull request on GitHub.

00:29:19.979 --> 00:29:25.979
And the easiest way to do that is just like proofread documentation because I'm terrible

00:29:25.979 --> 00:29:30.140
at proofreading and like whatever I'm working on recently I'm sure you can find it's like

00:29:30.140 --> 00:29:35.099
ridiculous small errors. Like that's not, you know, it's a useful contribution. It's not,

00:29:35.099 --> 00:29:39.739
you know, it's not amazingly valuable but that allows you to kind of get over that first hurdle

00:29:39.739 --> 00:29:44.939
of like how do I actually do all this stuff? What are the mechanics of creating a patch and submitting

00:29:44.939 --> 00:29:51.739
it to GitHub? So I really recommend that approach and then as you get like comfortable with that you

00:29:51.739 --> 00:29:56.939
can start to maybe look at some of the issues and try and create reprixes and then maybe start

00:29:56.939 --> 00:30:02.619
looking at the code a little bit yourself. Another great opportunity if you happen to be coming to

00:30:03.339 --> 00:30:11.579
PositConf in September and August or you live in Seattle, we have a Tidyverse Developer Day

00:30:12.380 --> 00:30:17.180
coming up which is just a day where, I'll put the link in the chat,

00:30:19.900 --> 00:30:25.660
the chat, where you can just come and try out that process in a very friendly supportive

00:30:25.660 --> 00:30:30.219
environment with tons of helpers around. So if you are interested and you can make it I'd say

00:30:31.020 --> 00:30:36.859
that's 100% the best way. Otherwise, you know, start small, figure out the mechanics of GitHub

00:30:36.859 --> 00:30:44.540
and then start trying to tackle some of the simpler issues. Cool, well yeah, thank you for

00:30:44.540 --> 00:30:49.099
your time and as I mentioned those questions we have around things like PositAcademy that we'll

00:30:49.099 --> 00:30:53.979
follow up with in an email. But yeah, thank you for your time Hadley and I'm looking forward to

00:30:54.780 --> 00:30:58.699
seeing your workshop and hearing you talk next month in Salzburg.

00:30:59.979 --> 00:31:07.339
Yeah, awesome, thanks James, thanks Edwin, thanks for coming everyone.

